{"cursor":"25715","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{taxobox |name = Helianthus annuus |image = Sunflower sky backdrop.jpg\n|image_width = 250px |regnum = Plantae |unranked_divisio = Angiosperms\n|unranked_classis = Eudicots |unranked_ordo = Asterids |ordo = Asterales\n|familia = Asteraceae |subfamilia = Helianthoideae |tribus = Heliantheae |genus\n= [[Helianthus]] |species = 'H. annuus' |binomial = Helianthus annuus\n|binomial_authority = L.\n|}}\n'Sunflower' ('Helianthus annuus') is an annual plant native to the Americas. It\npossesses a large inflorescence (flowering head), and its name is derived from\nthe flower's shape and image, which is often used to depict the sun. The plant\nhas a rough, hairy stem, broad, coarsely toothed, rough leaves and circular\nheads of flowers. The heads consist of many individual flowers which mature into\nseeds, often in the hundreds, on a receptacle base. From the Americas, sunflower\nseeds were brought to Europe in the 16th century, where, along with sunflower\noil, they became a widespread cooking ingredient. Leaves of the sunflower can be\nused as cattle feed, while the stems contain a fibre which may be used in paper\nproduction.\n","linknr":617,"url":"Sunflower","recorded":1362373038,"links":119,"instances":["plant","agriculture","botany"],"pdf":["http://www.cropj.com/karimmojeini_5_11_2011_1434_1440.pdf","http://www.pnas.org/content/105/17/6232.full.pdf"],"categories":["Annual plants","Articles with inconsistent citation formats","Agriculture in Mesoamerica","Butterfly food plants","Crops originating from Mexico","Edible nuts and seeds","Energy crops","Flora of Central America","Flora of Delaware","Flora of Maryland","Flora of Mexico","Flora of Pennsylvania","Flora of Virginia","Flora of Washington, D.C.","Flora of West Virginia","Flowers","Garden plants","Garden plants of North America","Helianthus|annuus","Honey plants","Medicinal plants","Phytoremediation plants","Botany"],"headings":["Structure","D